\v 8 \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w four|strong="G5064"\w* \w living|strong="G2226"\w* beings, \w each|strong="G2596"\w* \w one|strong="G1520"\w* \w of|strong="G2250"\w* \w them|strong="G3588"\w*, \w having|strong="G2192"\w* \w six|strong="G1803"\w* \w wings|strong="G4420"\w* apiece, \w were|strong="G1510"\w* \w full|strong="G1073"\w* \w of|strong="G2250"\w* \w eyes|strong="G3788"\w* \w around|strong="G2943"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w within|strong="G2081"\w*.\f + \fr 4:8 \ft The picture seems to be that the throne was not solid—the living beings moved in, through and around it; and they themselves were translucent—at least John could see that they had eyes \+nd inside\+nd* as well as outside.\f* \w And|strong="G2532"\w* \w they|strong="G2532"\w* \w take|strong="G2316"\w* \w no|strong="G3756"\w* \w rest|strong="G1510"\w*, \w day|strong="G2250"\w* \w or|strong="G2532"\w* \w night|strong="G3571"\w*, \w saying|strong="G3004"\w*:\f + \fr 4:8 \ft Most of the Greek manuscripts have the elders in chorus with the living beings here, but the best line of transmission has just the living beings repeating ‘holy’ endlessly, which agrees with verse nine.\f*  
\q1 “Holy, holy, holy;  
\q2 Holy, holy, holy;  
\q2 Holy, holy, holy;\f + \fr 4:8 \ft The manuscript evidence is badly divided here, but I take it that two of the tree main lines of independent transmission, including the best one, have “holy” nine times, instead of three. Surely it is more likely that ‘nine’ would be changed to ‘three’ than vice versa. In fact, try reading “holy” nine times in a row out loud—it starts to get uncomfortable! Since in the context the living ones are repeating themselves endlessly, the ‘nine’ is both appropriate and effective. Three ‘holies’ for each member of the Trinity.\f*  
\q1 \w The|strong="G2532"\w* \w Lord|strong="G2962"\w* \w God|strong="G2316"\w* \w Almighty|strong="G3841"\w*;  
